    story: '''
Wisnu adalah salah satu dari tiga dewa utama dalam Trimurti, yang bertanggung jawab memelihara dan menjaga keseimbangan alam semesta (dharma) di antara penciptaan oleh Brahma dan peleburan oleh Shiva. Dalam tradisi Waisnawa, ia dipandang sebagai dewa tertinggi yang berbaring di atas ular kosmik Sesha di lautan susu (Ksheera Sagara) bersama istrinya, Dewi Lakshmi.

Tugas utama Wisnu adalah menjaga tatanan kosmik dan turun ke dunia dalam wujud avatar setiap kali kejahatan mengancam mengalahkan kebajikan. Ia digambarkan berkulit biru dengan empat lengan yang masing-masing memegang sangkakala kerang (Panchajanya), cakra (Sudarshana Chakra), gada (Kaumodaki), dan bunga teratai, mengenakan permata Kaustubha dan kain kuning (Pitambara), serta mengendarai burung garuda. Sifatnya tenang, penuh welas asih, dan senantiasa berpihak pada kebenaran dan kesejahteraan makhluk hidup.

Salah satu kisah paling dikenal tentang Wisnu adalah ajarannya melalui Bhagavad Gita dalam wiracarita Mahabharata, ketika ia turun sebagai Krishna dan membimbing Arjuna tentang dharma, pengabdian (bhakti), dan hakikat jiwa sebelum pertempuran besar di Kurukshetra. Konsep sepuluh avatarnya (Dashavatara) menjadi salah satu pilar penting Waisnawa. Ia dipuja luas melalui perayaan seperti Diwali (terkait kepulangan Rama) dan Janmashtami (kelahiran Krishna), serta melalui kuil-kuil besar seperti Tirupati Venkateswara dan Jagannath Puri, dengan Vishnu Sahasranama (seribu nama Wisnu) yang dilantunkan sebagai bentuk pemujaan.''',
    storyEn: '''
Vishnu is one of the three principal deities of the Trimurti, responsible for preserving and maintaining the balance of the universe (dharma) between Brahma's creation and Shiva's dissolution. In the Vaishnava tradition he is regarded as the supreme deity, reclining upon the cosmic serpent Shesha in the ocean of milk (Ksheera Sagara) alongside his consort, the goddess Lakshmi.

Vishnu's central task is to uphold cosmic order and descend to earth in avatar form whenever evil threatens to overwhelm righteousness. He is depicted with blue skin and four arms holding a conch shell (Panchajanya), a discus (Sudarshana Chakra), a mace (Kaumodaki), and a lotus, wearing the Kaustubha jewel and yellow garments (Pitambara), and riding the eagle Garuda. His character is calm and compassionate, consistently siding with truth and the welfare of living beings.

One of the best-known episodes involving Vishnu is his teaching of the Bhagavad Gita within the epic Mahabharata, when he descends as Krishna to guide Arjuna on dharma, devotion (bhakti), and the true nature of the self before the great battle of Kurukshetra. The concept of his ten avatars, the Dashavatara, forms one of the central pillars of Vaishnavism. He is widely worshipped through festivals such as Diwali, linked to Rama's return, and Janmashtami, marking Krishna's birth, as well as through major temples such as Tirupati Venkateswara and Jagannath Puri, with the Vishnu Sahasranama, his thousand names, recited as an act of devotion.''',
