  God(
    id: '32',
    name: 'Kali',
    mythology: 'Hindu',
    title: 'Dewi Waktu & Kematian',
    titleEn: 'Goddess of Time & Death',
    symbol: '🖤',
    powers: ['Waktu', 'Kematian', 'Transformasi', 'Kebebasan', 'Kekuatan Gelap'],
    powersEn: ['Time', 'Death', 'Transformation', 'Liberation', 'Dark Power'],
    story: '''
Kali adalah wujud paling dahsyat dari Devi atau Shakti, terkait erat dengan waktu, kematian, dan penghancuran ego. Menurut Devi Mahatmya, ia muncul dari dahi Durga yang murka saat pertempuran melawan para asura, khususnya ketika menghadapi iblis Raktabija, dan dalam tradisi Shaktisme ia juga dipandang sebagai pendamping Shiva.

Sebagai dewi waktu dan kematian, Kali melambangkan kala—waktu yang melahap segalanya—serta jalan menuju pembebasan (moksha) melalui penghancuran ilusi (maya) dan ego. Ia digambarkan berkulit gelap kebiruan, mengenakan kalung tengkorak atau kepala terpenggal (mundamala), rok dari lengan-lengan terpotong, lidah menjulur, membawa pedang dan kepala terpenggal, serta sering digambarkan berdiri atau menari di atas tubuh Shiva. Penampilannya yang menyeramkan bersifat simbolis, mewakili kemenangan atas rasa takut akan kematian dan kebenaran hakiki di balik dunia ilusi.

Kisah terkenal tentang Kali adalah pertempurannya melawan Raktabija, iblis yang mampu menggandakan diri dari setiap tetes darahnya yang jatuh ke tanah; Kali meminum darahnya sebelum menyentuh tanah untuk mencegah penggandaan tersebut, namun kemudian ia menari dalam amukan yang tak terkendali hingga Shiva berbaring di bawah kakinya untuk menenangkannya—momen yang digambarkan dengan lidahnya yang menjulur karena terkejut. Kali menjadi pusat pemujaan penting dalam Shaktisme dan tradisi Tantra, khususnya di Benggala melalui Kuil Kalighat dan Dakshineswar, serta dirayakan melalui Kali Puja yang jatuh bersamaan dengan malam Diwali. Tokoh spiritual terkenal seperti Ramakrishna Paramahamsa dikenal sebagai penganut setia pemujaan Kali.''',
    storyEn: '''
Kali is the most fearsome form of Devi, or Shakti, closely associated with time, death, and the destruction of the ego. According to the Devi Mahatmya, she burst forth from Durga's furious forehead during battle against the asuras, particularly in the confrontation with the demon Raktabija, and within Shaktism she is also regarded as a consort of Shiva.

As goddess of time and death, Kali embodies kala, time that consumes all things, and represents the path to liberation (moksha) through the destruction of illusion (maya) and ego. She is depicted with dark, blue-black skin, wearing a garland of skulls or severed heads (mundamala) and a skirt of severed arms, with her tongue protruding, carrying a sword and a severed head, and often shown standing or dancing upon the body of Shiva. Her terrifying appearance is symbolic, representing victory over the fear of death and the ultimate reality that lies beneath the world of illusion.

The most famous story of Kali is her battle against Raktabija, a demon capable of multiplying himself from every drop of his blood that touched the ground; Kali drank his blood before it could fall in order to prevent this replication, but then danced in an uncontrollable frenzy until Shiva lay beneath her feet to calm her, a moment depicted by her tongue protruding in shock. Kali is a central figure of worship within Shaktism and the Tantric tradition, especially in Bengal through the Kalighat and Dakshineswar temples, and is celebrated through Kali Puja, held on the same night as Diwali. Notable spiritual figures such as Ramakrishna Paramahamsa were renowned devotees of Kali worship.''',
    imageUrl:
