    symbol: '🪈',
    powers: ['Cinta', 'Kebijaksanaan', 'Sihir', 'Strategi', 'Seni Musik'],
    powersEn: ['Love', 'Wisdom', 'Magic', 'Strategy', 'Musical Arts'],
    story: '''
Krishna adalah avatar kedelapan Wisnu, lahir dari pasangan Devaki dan Vasudeva di Mathura, namun dibesarkan oleh orang tua angkatnya, Yashoda dan Nanda, di Vrindavan dan Gokul untuk menyelamatkannya dari pamannya sendiri, Raja Kamsa, yang berusaha membunuhnya sesuai ramalan yang mengancam kekuasaannya.

Sebagai perwujudan cinta ilahi, Krishna dikenal melalui masa mudanya yang penuh keceriaan dan kasih bersama Radha serta para gopi di Vrindavan, sekaligus sebagai penasihat bijak dan ahli strategi dalam Mahabharata pada masa dewasanya. Ia digambarkan berkulit biru gelap, mengenakan mahkota bulu merak, memainkan seruling yang memikat siapa pun yang mendengarnya, serta mengenakan permata Kaustubha dan kain kuning. Sifatnya jenaka dan nakal semasa kecil—dikenal sebagai Makhan Chor, si pencuri mentega—namun tampil bijaksana dan tenang sebagai penasihat di usia dewasa.

Kisah paling terkenal tentang Krishna adalah penyampaian Bhagavad Gita kepada Arjuna di medan pertempuran Kurukshetra dalam Mahabharata, mengajarkan tentang dharma, jalan pengabdian (bhakti yoga), dan hakikat sejati diri manusia. Ia juga dikenal karena membunuh Kamsa, paman tirani yang mengancam nyawanya sejak lahir. Krishna menjadi figur sentral dalam Waisnawa dan dipuja luas melalui perayaan Janmashtami serta Holi yang berkaitan dengan kisah cintanya bersama Radha, dengan kuil-kuil besar seperti Dwarkadhish serta situs ziarah Vrindavan dan Mathura yang terus ramai dikunjungi hingga kini.''',
    storyEn: '''
Krishna is the eighth avatar of Vishnu, born to Devaki and Vasudeva in Mathura but raised by his foster parents, Yashoda and Nanda, in Vrindavan and Gokul to protect him from his own uncle, King Kamsa, who sought to kill him in accordance with a prophecy that threatened his throne.

As the embodiment of divine love, Krishna is known for a youth filled with playfulness and affection alongside Radha and the gopis of Vrindavan, and equally as a wise counselor and strategist in the Mahabharata during his adult years. He is depicted with dark blue skin, a crown of peacock feathers, a flute whose music enchants all who hear it, and the Kaustubha jewel and yellow garments. He is mischievous and playful as a child, known as Makhan Chor, the butter thief, yet appears wise and composed as an adviser in adulthood.

The most celebrated story of Krishna is his delivery of the Bhagavad Gita to Arjuna on the battlefield of Kurukshetra in the Mahabharata, teaching dharma, the path of devotion (bhakti yoga), and the true nature of the self. He is also known for slaying Kamsa, the tyrannical uncle who had threatened his life since birth. Krishna is a central figure of Vaishnavism and is widely worshipped through the festivals of Janmashtami and Holi, the latter linked to his love story with Radha, with major temples such as Dwarkadhish and the pilgrimage sites of Vrindavan and Mathura continuing to draw devotees to this day.''',
    imageUrl: '',
    category: 'Avatar',
